Node.Notes: The evil men are the same group as "my adversaries and my foes."
This infinitival clause is either in apposition to "it" (object of previous clause) or is the object of another assumed "I seek."
Because of "gaze," probably something of a pleasant/favorable appearance like beauty/glory.
Dwelling place/shelter, apparently (along with "tent" in the next clause) referring to the temple as a refuge.
A figure of safety, high beyond enemy attacks.
"My head will be lfted up above my enemies around me," in the sense of triumph over those enemies.
Many see parental abandonment expressed as possibility, not fact; so "if/though." "For/because" is probable (parental abandonment) grounds plea of previous verse for God not to abandon the psalmist.
Gather, in the sense of welcome/receive.

Marked as doubtful in Masoretic text itself and omitted by five Hebrew manuscripts and LXX. Many omit it. If genuine, could express something like "[In light of the overwhelming attacks of my enemies, I would have given up hope] unless I am confident that I would see …"
